Interpretable Neural Networks for Shot Selection

Thu 25 April 2019
By Joshuah Kapilivsky

A single point of tennis is loaded with decisions for each player:

  • Should I hit a forehand or backhand?
  • Should I hit it with topspin or slice?
  • Which way should I hit it?
  • Should I approach the net?
  • Should I move left, expecting a shot to my backhand?
  • Should I hit this shot to the same place I hit the last one?
  • Can I pass this player with one shot, or do I need to do it in two?

As I've written before, I find studying player decisions more interesting than studying outcomes. There's already a vast body of knowledge showing that top players hit more winners, make fewer errors, or force more errors than their opponents. Sophisticated analysis that comes to some variant of that conclusion isn't that insightful; players don't need to be taught that winning more points is important. What is insightful, however, is how top players create positive outcomes. It's evident that being more athletic, more technically skilled, or more consistent will improve your chances of positive outcomes. Instead, I'd like to know about how athletic, skilled, and consistent players actually deploy their talents to win points.

Shot selection encapsulates a broad collection of repeated decisions, making it a rich area for study. At a basic level, shot selection captures where the player is relative to the ball (backhand side), how the player strikes the ball (slice), and the direction that the player strikes the ball (to opponent's backhand). We can even look at shot selection across many consecutive shots to reveal more complex player tactics (i.e., an aggressive player might try to move their opponent from sideline to sideline).

Predictive Power and Interpretability¶

When designing a model, one has to consider a pracitcal tradeoff between predictive power and interpretability. Consider two possible applications for a shot selection model:

  1. A tennis-playing robot is trying to select its next shot (or predict its opponent's next shot) in real-time
  2. A human is trying to improve their shot selection and predictions out on the court

The optimal models for the two applications are quite different. The robot's capacity for real-time calculation is incredibly high, as is its capacity to memorize the model, so the robot is best served by a model that is as predictive as possible. The human will not have time to crunch numbers on court, so they would be best served by a few pieces of key insight, generally in the form of heuristics.

With sufficiently large datasets that are generated from complex patterns, one usually faces a tradeoff between predictive power and interpretability. This tradeoff can be tuned based on the class of model used, the parameters of the model, and even the objective function used to evaluate and optimize the model.

In this analysis, I am most interested in that second application for a shot selection model: I'd like to create basic heuristics for how tennis is played. I do not own a tennis-playing robot, or even a program that plays a virtual tennis match. I am most interested in an interpretable model that is reasonably predictive.

I frame shot selection as a classification problem, starting with whether a player will hit a forehand or backhand. I use neural networks to predict these classes. Neural networks are generally considered to be strongly predictive but uninterpretable. I've chosen to constrain the structure of the neural networks I use, as well as the predictive power I can achieve, to create models that are interpretable. I use these models to describe basic heuristics for shot selection at the professional level. My models rely on real shot-by-shot tennis data from The Match Charting Project, created by Jeff Sackmann, creator of Tennis Abstract and the blog Heavy Topspin.

I've included below the basic functions that I will repeatedly call throughout this analysis, as well as a look at the dataset I'm using. If you are uninterested in these details, you may proceed directly to Part 1.

def create_train_test(label, sample, train_size=25000):
    """
    Splits available data into training and testing datasets.
    Labels are also separated from the features used to predict the label.
    """

    features = [col for col in sample.columns if col not in label]
    X = pd.get_dummies(sample[features])
    y = sample[label]

    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test \
        = train_test_split(X, y,
                           test_size=len(y) - train_size,
                           random_state=1)

    print('Number of Training Samples: ' + str(len(y_train)))
    print('Number of Testing Samples: ' + str(len(y_test)))

    return X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test


def train_grid_cv(model, grid_params, X_train,
                  y_train, cv=5, scoring='f1_weighted'):
    """
    Performs model selection using cross validation
    with a grid search of values.
    """
    clf = GridSearchCV(model, grid_params, cv=cv, iid=False,
                       return_train_score=True, scoring=scoring)
    clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

    return clf


# The grid search selects model from these network structures
# and values for alpha (regularization term).
ann = MLPClassifier(random_state=1)
alphas = np.logspace(-2, 1, 4)
hidden_layer_sizes = [(3), (5), (7), (3, 2), (5, 2)]

def visualize_ann(coefs, input_columns, cmap='PuOr',
                  n_dec=2, figsize=(12, 6), square=True,
                  output_labels=None, rotate_labels=False):
    """
    Creates multiple heatmaps to visualize network weights.
    """

    f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=figsize, ncols=len(coefs))
    for layer in range(len(coefs)):
        if layer == 0:
            layer_df = round(pd.DataFrame(coefs[layer], input_columns), n_dec)
        else:
            layer_df = round(pd.DataFrame(coefs[layer]), n_dec)

        if layer != len(coefs) - 1:
            ax[layer].set_title('Hidden Layer ' + str(layer))
        else:
            ax[layer].set_title('Output Layer')
        sns.heatmap(layer_df, ax=ax[layer], annot=True,
                    square=square, cmap=cmap, center=0, cbar=False,
                    vmin=-2, vmax=2)
        ax[layer].xaxis.set_tick_params(bottom=False)
        ax[layer].yaxis.set_tick_params(rotation=0, left=False)

    if output_labels:
        ax[len(coefs)-1].set_xticklabels(output_labels)
    if rotate_labels:
        ax[len(coefs)-1].xaxis.set_tick_params(rotation=90)


def visualize_neuron(
    coefs, layer, neuron,
    labels=['Backhand (Topspin)', 'Forehand (Topspin)',
            'Slice Forehand', 'Slice Backhand',
            'Approach to Forehand', 'Approach Down Middle',
            'Approach to Backhand', 'To Forehand',
            'To Middle', 'To Backhand'
            ]):
    """
    Creates a single row heatmap to visualize a single neuron.

    This is a useful tool to teach someone how to interpret
    the visualization of an entire neural network.
    """

    f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 1))

    weights = pd.DataFrame(coefs[layer]).iloc[:, [neuron]].transpose()
    sns.heatmap(round(weights, 2), ax=ax, annot=True,
                square=True, cmap='PuOr', center=0, cbar=False,
                vmin=-2, vmax=2)
    ax.set_xticklabels(labels, rotation=30, ha='right')
    ax.yaxis.set_visible(False)
    ax.set_title('Hidden Layer ' + str(layer)
                 + ', Neuron ' + str(neuron) + ' ',
                 fontsize=16)


def plot_tuning_curves(clf, y_test, X_test, n_bins=10,
                       figsize=(12, 6), colormap='cool', labels=None):
    """
    Plots calibration curve, distribution of predicted values,
    and ROC curve for a classifier.

    A single curve is plotted in each axis for a binary classifier.
    A curve for each class is plotted in each axis in the case
    of a multiclass classifier.
    """

    f = plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
    gs = gridspec.GridSpec(nrows=6, figure=f, ncols=2)
    ax_calib = f.add_subplot(gs[0:4, 0])
    ax_bins = f.add_subplot(gs[4:6, 0])
    ax_roc = f.add_subplot(gs[:, 1])
    cmap = plt.cm.get_cmap(colormap)
    y_probs = clf.predict_proba(X_test)
    classes = clf.classes_
    if not labels:
        labels = classes

    if len(classes) == 2:
        classes_shown = 1
    else:
        classes_shown = len(classes)

    for i in range(classes_shown):
        color = cmap(i / (y_probs.shape[1] - 1))
        frac_pos, mpv = calibration_curve(y_test == classes[i], y_probs[:, i],
                                          n_bins=n_bins)
        ax_calib.plot(mpv, frac_pos, c=color, lw=3, marker='o',
                      label=labels[i])
        ax_bins.hist(y_probs[:, i], range=(0, 1), bins=n_bins, histtype="step",
                     color=color, lw=3)

        fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test == classes[i], y_probs[:, i])
        roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
        ax_roc.plot(fpr, tpr, color=color, lw=3,
                    label='ROC curve (area = %0.2f)' % roc_auc)

    ax_calib.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], c='k', linestyle='--')
    ax_calib.set_xlim(xmin=0, xmax=1)
    ax_calib.set_ylim(ymin=0, ymax=1.05)
    ax_calib.set_xlabel('Mean Predicted Value')
    ax_calib.set_ylabel('Fraction of Positives')
    ax_calib.set_title('Calibration Curve')
    if classes_shown > 1:
        ax_calib.legend(loc="lower right")

    ax_bins.set_xlim(xmin=0, xmax=1)
    ax_bins.set_xlabel('Predicted Value')
    ax_bins.set_ylabel('Count')

    ax_roc.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], c='k', linestyle='--')
    ax_roc.set_xlim(xmin=0, xmax=1)
    ax_roc.set_ylim(ymin=0, ymax=1.05)
    ax_roc.set_xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    ax_roc.set_ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    ax_roc.set_title('Receiver Operating Characteristic')
    ax_roc.legend(loc="lower right")

    f.tight_layout()

Part 1: An Interpretable Neural Network for Forehand/Backhand¶

I begin with an introductory example of a neural network that predicts whether a player will hit a forehand or backhand. This classification is agnostic of spin and only includes ground strokes (ignores drop shots, volleys, half-volleys, overheads, etc.). To keep things simple, the model is only for men's matches played between two right handed players, and the selection of incoming shots, incoming directions, and outgoing shots is limited.

Model Design¶

A neural network has three basic sets of layers: an input layer, an arbitrary number of hidden layers, and an output layer. One can think of this as expanding on a regression model. While a regression model creates a single output from input features from the dataset, each neuron in a layer of neural network creates a single output from input features. In the case of the first hidden layer, the inputs to each neuron are the input features from the dataset. The inputs to neurons in the hidden layers and the output layer are the outputs from prior neurons. This is like chaining the output of multiple regression models as the input for other regression models. This is perhaps best understood with a series of heatmaps.

In [5]:

This neural network has 10 inputs, one hidden layer with three neurons, and a single output neuron that creates the binary output (Forehand/Backhand). The inputs are all binary flags describing the shot prior to the one predicted. For example, if we used the network to predict whether a player would hit a forehand or backhand in response to a topspin backhand hit to their backhand side, the input would take a value of 1 for "Backhand (Topspin)" and "To Backhand" and a value of 0 for the other 8 input features.

Each neuron is represented by a vertical slice of a heatmap. Let's walk through each neuron in the hidden layer one at a time.

In [6]:
visualize_neuron(simple_clf.best_estimator_.coefs_, 0, 0)

This neuron activates when the prior shot is hit to the forehand, whether it is an approach or not. Activation increases if the prior shot is a forehand or slice, particularly if it is a backhand slice. An incoming topspin backhand or incoming shot to the middle or backhand shot inhibits this neuron's activation.

Each neuron in this analysis is a rectified linear unit (ReLU). That means the neuron's output takes a value of 0 for any negative activation; otherwise it takes the value of the activation. The activation is equal to the dot product of the weights and the inputs. In this case, that is simply the sum of the relevant weights because all the inputs are binary flags. Here's some examples:

  1. A slice backhand hit to the backhand side would result in an output of max(0, 1 - 0.55) = 0.45
  2. A slice backhand hit to the forehand side would result in an output of max(0, 1 + 1.5) = 2.5
  3. A topspin forehand hit to the backhand side would result in an output of max(0, 0.32 - 0.55) = 0
  4. A topspin backhand hit to the backhand side would result in an output of max(0, -0.14 - 0.55) = 0

If we look ahead to the output layer, we can see that this neuron (0 on y axis) has a positive weight for the output neuron (positive outputs from the output neuron predict a forehand). Output from this neuron increases the predicted probability of the shot being a forehand. Looking at the weights and the examples above, that matches our intuition. A forehand reply is likely if the ball is hit to a player's a forehand or if slice allows the player to hit forehand from the backhand side of the court.

In [7]:
visualize_neuron(simple_clf.best_estimator_.coefs_, 0, 1)

This neuron also activates under similar circumstances, though the weights are subtly different. This may seem frustrating for interpretability, but it is an important concept to understand: the neurons are supposed to combine to create a calibrated predicted probability. This means that there might be similar neurons with slight contrasts.

In this case, the neuron activates under most of the same circumstances. However, it treats backhands, both topspin and slice, differently from the prior neuron. This neuron would activate for a topspin backhand hit to the middle of the court. It also would not activate for a slice backhand hit to the backhand side.

By itself, this neuron does not necessarily indicate that slice backhands hit to the backhand side are more or less likely to result in forehand replies. It merely indicates that there is a pattern in the data that is best captured by a neuron that ignores (output would be 0) these types of shots. Outputs from all neurons are combined to make the final prediction, so one must look at all the neurons together to see if a given pattern makes a forehand reply more likely.

In [8]:
visualize_neuron(simple_clf.best_estimator_.coefs_, 0, 2)

This last neuron only activates for topspin forehands hit to the middle of the court or the backhand side. Additionally, the activation is greatest when the shot is hit to the backhand side, especially if it is an approach shot to the backhand side. The topspin forehand is generally a player's most powerful shot, and an approach shot generally indicates the opponent has a favorable position inside the court. This neuron activates in situations when the player has no choice but to hit a backhand.

This neuron has a negative weight in the output layer. This makes sense because the neuron indicates situations where a backhand response is more likely, making a forehand response less likely.

Turning to the output layer, we see that the network is basically combining three different models to make a more refined prediction than any single neuron could. This insight leads to two complementary intuitions. First, a neural network is a form of ensemble model. This is basically like the wisdom of crowds; generally one can make stronger assessments by aggregating assessments from numerous sources. Second, hidden layers behave as feature engineers. A hidden layer does not necessarily classify cases directly. It creates a sophisticated internal representation that is useful for downstream classification.

Neuron 2 is not a model for predicting forehands. It is a model for powerful shots to the backhand side. That feature is useful, in turn, in predicting whether a shot will be a forehand or backhand.

One could have designed a number of sophisiticated features and inputted them directly into a single layer model, such as a logistic regression. However, this practice is challenging and unreliable. How many features should I make, and what should each feature be? Instead, I've used a neural network to do that feature engineering for me, constraining the structure so that the features I get are not overly complex. As I show in Part 5, if I allow the neural network to take on a more sophisticated structure, say by adding hidden layers, then I will get neurons that create features that interact in more complex ways and may not be easily interpretable. Each neuron will still be engineering features, but these features may not correspond to distinct human concepts about tennis.

Model Performance¶

Now that I've walked through interpreting the above neural network, it's time to discuss its performance. An interpretable model is of no use to us if it doesn't actually capture the data. However, a discussion of the best ways to assess model performance is not the focus of this article.

All of the neural networks in this article are selected using cross validation with a grid search of hidden layer sizes and values for the regularization term. The selected model is the combination of parameters with the highest average value for the F1 score on the 5 testing folds. The score reported with the figure of the network weights is the F1 score on the testing dataset. The F1 score is the harmonic average of the precision (fraction of predicted positives that are actually postive) and recall (fraction of actual postives that are predicted positive). Depending on the application, one would likely want to weight one of these factors over the other.

I've also included three charts related to performance for each model. The three panels are the calibration curve, the distribution of predicted values, and the receiver operating characteristic curve.

In [9]:
plot_tuning_curves(simple_clf, y_test, X_test)

The calibration curve is a tool to assess when the model is over or underconfident. It compares the probabilities assigned by the model against the observed probabilities. For example, we can pool all the cases where the model predicts that the next shot has an 80% chance of being a forehand, and then we can see how often those cases are actually forehands. A value of 80% would signify perfect calibration, a value above 80% would indicate underconfidence, and a value below 80% would indicate overconfidence. In general, a well-calibrated model will have a calibration curve that tracks the dotted line (Fraction of Positives = Mean Predicted Value).

The lower left panel shows the distribution of predicted values. This model seldom assigns probabilities between 10 and 20% and between 50 and 60%. It is therefore unsurprising that these are the regions of the calibration curve that deviate most from the dotted line; they have the smallest sample size.

The right panel shows the receiver operating characteristic (ROC). The ROC shows the tradeoff between true positives and false positives. The ROC for a random model would lie on the dotted line. A greater area under the curve indicates greater diagnostic ability.

Part 2: Expanding the Input Feature Space for Interpretable Forehand/Backhand Models¶

Now that I've introduced the key concepts and methodologies, I'm going to build a similar model, this time for a broader range of situations. This model makes forehand and backhand predictions for men and women, on the primary three playing surfaces, regardless of the handedness of either player.

The first thing you are likely to notice is that the weights for the first neuron are all 0s. This is due to two related factors:

  1. While adding more neurons will always improve the in sample performance, it won't always improve the out of sample performance. Thus cross validation selected a single hidden layer with 5 neurons, not one with 3 or 7. (I did not give it the option to select 4 or 6 neurons).
  2. The neural network objective function includes a regularization term. This is basically a penalty term for the complexity of the model. Model weights are pulled to 0, and weights that are not sufficiently useful (relative to the regularization term) eventually take a value of 0. If I had included a single hidden layer with 4 neurons as an option in my grid search, that likely would have been the model selected.

The second thing you are likely to notice is that the weights for the player handedness variables have the greatest magnitudes. Relatedly, the opponent handedness variables have relatively small weights. This is specific to this prediction problem: if we know that a shot has been hit to the player's right, then whether the player is right or left handed will be a crucial determinant of whether that shot is a forehand or backhand. The prior model suggests that those two pieces of information are not sufficient for predictive performance, but they are clearly some of the most important factors. In Part 3, I will show an interpretable neural network for shot direction, and we will see more factors, including the opponent's handedness, playing a larger role.

I interpret neuron 3 as coding right handers being pressured on the backhand side, likely resulting in a backhand. Neurons 1, 2, and 4 have similar weights for prior shot direction and handedness. I think their distinction is in what they code for gender, surface, and incoming shot type (both wing and spin). It's interesting to note that weights for slice shots generally agree within a neuron, suggesting that whether the incoming shot was a forehand or backhand matters less if it was a slice.

Additionally, the rank order of weights for the three surfaces is consistent across neurons. My prior is that playing on clay, which is generally the slowest surface with the highest bounces, would give players the most time to hit their shot, thereby weakening the importance of the incoming shot's direction, spin, etc. Relatedly, I'd expect that grass, which generally plays faster and has low, unpredictable bounces, would give players the least time to do something like hit a run-around forehand. Though interpretation is difficult here, the rank order of these weights suggests that these differences in surfaces are meaningful and my prior that clay affords more options than hard court, which affords (slightly) more options than grass, is plausible.

Part 3: An Interpretable Neural Network for Shot Direction¶

Predicting forehands and backhands was a useful starter example, but it got less interesting when the model was dominated by incoming shot direction and whether the payer is right or left handed. I'm now going to turn to something that gets closer to actual on court tactics: predicting the direction of a shot. The input features are the same as above, but now they are used to predict something different.

The shot-by-shot data codes shot direction into three basic categories: to the forehand side, to the middle, and to the backhand side. These directions are defined in the context of right handed players, but since they apply to righties and lefties alike, I am going to refer to them as to the deuce court, to the middle, and to the ad court, respectively. The directions are imprecisely defined, mostly because the data is crowdsourced and encoded manually, but the middle should be considered the middle 40% of the court, leaving 30% each for the deuce and ad court shots. Shots to the middle of the court are not necessarily hit perpendicular to the net; a player may hit an angled shot from out wide to the middle of the court.

This is the first model that I've shown that performs multiclass (not binary) prediction. You will see multiple output neurons, one corresponding to each possible class. As is standard with neural networks, the outputs of each of these neurons are converted to predicted class probabilities using the softmax function. This is basically a way to map multiple input values of arbitrary range into multiple values between 0 and 1, ensuring that they all sum to 1. The model is evaluated using the weighted average of the F1 scores and number of members of each class.

Let's start with the output layer and try to peel this apart for insights. The output layer is made up of 3 neurons, each taking in the same 7 inputs. The pattern of weights for the seven inputs is fairly complimentary; six of the eight possible comibinations of signs for each input are present. Let's start with the neurons from the hidden layer that have a positive weight for just one direction.

Activation from neuron 3 increases activation for only shots to the ad court. This neuron is activated by incoming shots to the ad court. Activation is greater for left handed players, and right handed opponents, particularly if the incoming shot is a slice backhand and the match is played on clay. This captures a few common threads in tennis:

  1. It is generally safer to hit a cross court shot than a down the line shot. This is because the ball has farther to go, making it easier to clear the net and land in, and because the net is actually lower in the center of the court than it is near the alleys. The most conservative option when facing an incoming shot to the ad court is thus to hit it cross court, heading to the ad court.
  2. The backhand is generally an opponent's weaker wing, and players try to target it. If the opponent is right handed, then hitting to the ad court finds their backhand.
  3. Left handers are particularly likely to benefit from hitting to a right hander's backhand. This makes the opponent's safest shot back to the lefty's forehand, locking the two player's into a cross court exchange between the lefty's preferred wing and the righty's weaker wing.
  4. A slice is generally used as a defensive shot to get more time to get back in position before the next shot. This also allows the opponent more time to take an advantageous court position, such as moving in, ensuring their next shot can be a forehand, or choosing the direction to hit the ball. This means that a player trying to hit to the ad court will have more freedom to do so when facing an incoming slice.
  5. Clay courts are generally slower with higher bounces. This also means that a player has more freedom to hit to the ad court when they wish to.

That's a lot of useful inferences that can be made from just this single neuron. This highlights an interesting facet of the neural network: it functionally creates interaction terms relevant to the prediction problem. If this were a logistic regression problem, we might make new features that combine other binary variables, such as a new variable for a righty playing against a lefty or for a righty facing shot to ad court. Without these interactions, we wouldn't be able to make these combinatoric evaluations from a simple sum of 20 weights. But searching all the possible pairings and trios of variables would be a nightmare for interpretation and generalization. Instead, the neural network learns the interactions that are most important, and it ignores the rest.

The weights for neuron 4 follow a pattern that can be explained with similar logic. This neuron mostly deals with the opposite scenario: a right handed player, a left handed opponent, with an incoming shot to the deuce side. The strategy here is to hit off the preferred wing (forehand) to the opponent's weaker wing (backhand). We again see that playing on clay or facing an incoming slice give the player more freedom to hit to the direction they want (the deuce court).

Some of the other neurons from the hidden layer are more difficult to interpret individually. For example, consider neuron 1. Activation of this neuron decreases activation for all three neurons in the output layer. It is activated by:

  1. topspin backhands
  2. slices
  3. approach shots (but not those down the middle)
  4. left handed players
  5. men's matches
  6. matches on clay or hard courts

This doesn't seem to reflect a single particular strategy. In my interpretation, these might be scenarios that simply make the direction of the next shot direction harder to predict. Topspin backhands are generally the weaker topspin shot, we've already discussed how slices give the opponent more time, and clay and hard courts have more predictable bounces and are slower than grass. These are all scenarios where the player has more choice to redirect the shot.

That only covers three of the six factors I listed. What about the other three?

Does this mean that men redirect rallies more than women do? I don't know. This is one of the limitations of this type of interpretation. This isn't an actual experiment, and if you aren't careful, you can come up with any number of seemingly plausible mechanistic explanations for the weights observed. For example, if you have the prior that men's tennis players are stronger, more aggressive, or more skilled than women's tennis players, then you might interpret this as "men are more something, so they redirect rallies more than women do". But one could have also seen the reverse case, where the weight is positive for women and negative for men. In that case, the same person might say, "men are more something, so it is harder to redirect rallies in a men's match." Do men actually redirect rallies more then women do? I don't know. In a situation like this, it's plausible that these two weights have these values because it balances some other factor in the model, and reading into it will only confirm whatever biases you already have.

Well, what about lefties? It's plausible that lefties are truly unpredictable. But I think it has to do with the imbalance between the number of left-handed and right-handed players. This imbalance leads to two possibilities:

  1. There simply isn't enough data on left-handed players to make good predictions.
  2. When given limited resources to make predictions in a complex space, it is most efficient to focus on scenarios that occur more frequently.

The reality might be a mix of the two.

I think there is something to be said about the pattern of approach shots here. Most of the explanations we've looked at that make the next shot direction harder to predict have been focused on scenarios that give the player more time to choose. That's clearly not the case here; an approach shot usually indicates that the opponent has a favorable court position that they are trying to leverage into an even more favorable position at the net. A player on the baseline facing an opponent at the net is unlikely to win a prolonged rally. In this case, while the player likely has less time to make a shot direction choice, their opponent has forced them into a high risk, high reward situation. The player needs to hit a passing shot (or a two shot pass). Either way, the time for playing conservatively or slowly opening up an advantage is over; the player must take bold action.

I'm not going to interpret the remaining four neurons. At some point, reading into every individual value is a form of overfitting. A neural network is complex and interconnected, and each weight is dependent on the input data (which has some randomness) and the way the model was built (which also has some randomness). One weight might take its value simply because another weight has a different value and that's the combination that makes the most accurate prediction on the training data. As I mentioned in Part 1, while the neural network is performing a type of feature engineering, the features it creates may not be tied to specific human conceptions, even if the model is (relatively) simple.

In [13]:
plot_tuning_curves(dir_clf, y_test, X_test,
                   labels=['To Deuce Court', 'Down Middle', 'To Ad Court'])

I've plotted the same three panels on model performance as before, but this time each class has its own lines. We can see that the model is reasonably well calibrated, and it doesn't make predictions for any class that are below 10% or above 70%. This isn't all that surprising, given that the probabilities for each class must sum to 1 for each case. The predictions may be less confident simply because the classification may be more difficult.

The area under the ROC curves shows that the model is better able to make predictions for shots to the deuce and ad courts than for shots down the middle. That isn't particularly surprising, as players can hit to the middle from more scenarios than they can hit to either side.

Part 4: Player Specific Shot Direction Models¶

Below I'm going to show two shot direction models, one for Roger Federer and one for Rafael Nadal. As the input data is crowdsourced and generated by hand, the matches available reflect the popularity of the players. These are the two players with the most charted matches.

I'm not going to interpret these models individually, but I encourage you to take a look and see if anything interesting catches your eye. I conclude this section with a discussion of the merits of these player specific models below.

Now that we have models for two different players, what comparisons are fair or insightful? Honestly, the list is fairly limited. While each model is relatively interpretable, their complexity, and the loose constraints in their construction, make comparisons difficult. The individual neurons can have completely different meanings in the two models, so comparing the weights isn't illuminating. In fact, the number of hidden layers or neurons in the "optimal" model shown here doesn't really tell us anything either. We could consider making some commentary about possible differences between players only in extreme cases where we find two sufficiently contrasting patterns of weights.

Does comparing the model scores tell us anything? Not really, the testing data is fairly different. If the predictive accuracy for the two players is different, does that mean that one player is more predictable than the other? Would it mean that one model is better than the other? Could it just be random? That line of analysis would likely raise more questions than it answers.

However, this idea leads us to something more useful. If the issue is different data for evaluation, we could try making comparisons using each trained model to make predictions on identical sets of input data. For example, we could use the Federer model to predict the probability that he would hit to the deuce court in response to an incoming topspin backhand in the deuce court against a left handed opponent on clay. We could then use the Nadal model to predict the probability of the same decision in response to the same situation. In fact, we could go one step further, comparing the probabilities for each of the three shot directions in response to a robust array of inputs.

That comparison is not based on the network weights, or even the network structure at all. If we want to make these types of comparisons, we could do so using any model construction, not just neural nets, with an arbitrary degree of complexity. We'd no longer be constrained to neural networks that are simple enough to interpret their weights. Unfortunately, I'm not going to perform that analysis here.

What have we learned here?¶

There were two basic goals for this article. First, it incrementally built up an intuition for how a trained neural network generates predictions based on input values. This intuition is essential to using a neural network; while they are often treated as a black box, one should still know the general types of operations occurring within that box. As we've seen here, neural networks can quickly become too complex to allow for interpretation of their weights. In practice, studying a neural network is a sort of science experiment. If you want to know the effect of hitting a slice on your opponent's next shot, you can compare the prediction resulting from your incoming shot with slice and with topspin. Performing many experiments such as these allows you to begin to characterize the predictions without needing to know how they are generated.

The second goal was to show how it is plausible that neural networks would work at all. This was accomplished by showing that constrained neural networks uncover some of the same intutions about tennis that humans do. The exercise of interpreting neural network weights has limited value, but the heuristics generated here show that these types of models operate using some of the same basic principles that we use.

As an added bonus, if you did not know much about tennis strategy, you likely picked up some useful heuristics from this analysis: expect players to target your weaker wing, expect cross court shots, and if you hit a slice, expect the unexpected. Coaches, players, and fans have been saying those things for decades, but now you have evidence that those heuristics are predictive.

Epilogue: "Uninterpretable" Neural Networks¶

I've mentioned numerous times how I had to constrain the structure of the above neural networks to ensure that they would be interpretable. I show below the standard figures for a neural network constructed with far weaker constraints. This model tries to predict if Roger Federer will hit a topspin forehand, topspin backhand, slice forehand, or slice backhand in response to the usual features. These four classes have a pseudo-2x2 design (Topspin/Slice and Forehand/Backhand). Additionally, I have expanded the number of input features available to the model; the prior two shots are now provided as inputs.

This is a task that a neural network should be able to do really well. One could envision a network that predicts topspin versus slice and forehand verus backhand in a hidden layer, and then combines those in the output layer. In reality, when unconstrained, the resulting network is more accurate and more complex. This model likely performs well, but interpretation of the weights is unlikely to be useful.
